# Authoring `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`

## File naming

`<NN>-<scope>.mdc` where `NN` is a 2-digit priority:

| Range | Purpose                                                |
| ----- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| 00–09 | Universal (`alwaysApply: true`). **Cap at 200 words.** |
| 10–19 | Backend scoped                                          |
| 20–29 | Frontend scoped                                         |
| 30–39 | Infra / CI / observability                             |
| 40–49 | Workflow / process (description-triggered)             |
| 50–89 | Reserved for future domains                            |
| 90–99 | Meta (this rule lives here)                            |

## Frontmatter

```yaml
---
description: One sentence semantic summary. Used to auto-route rules to a prompt.
globs: comma,separated,glob,patterns  # leave empty if description-triggered
alwaysApply: false                    # only true for 00–09 core rules
---
```

- **`description`** — write as the agent would: "Use when …". Be specific so semantic routing is reliable.
- **`globs`** — auto-attach when matching files are in the working set. Use `,` separator, no quotes.
- **`alwaysApply`** — `true` only for the universal constitution. Every always-applied byte taxes every prompt.

## Body

- Markdown headings; no prose paragraphs longer than 3 lines.
- Lists and tables over prose.
- Examples in fenced code blocks with a language tag.
- Cross-reference other rules by filename (e.g. "see `11-backend-models.mdc`") rather than copy/pasting.
- No prose like "remember to" — write directives ("**Do** X", "**Forbidden**: Y").

## Anti-patterns

- Putting code generation templates in rules — those belong in `scripts/` or `docs/`.
- `alwaysApply: true` on anything domain-specific — taxes the global token budget.
- Duplicating content across rules — link, don't copy.
- Multi-paragraph "philosophy" sections — irrelevant at inference time.
